# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dicom-imaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOM standard has been widely adopted by hospitals, large clinics, and the medical software industry.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] It is sometimes used in smaller-scale applications, such as dentists' and doctors' offices.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM is also used in veterinary medicine and in research.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA) holds the copyright to the published standard, which was developed by the DICOM Standards Committee (which includes some NEMA members).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] It is also known as NEMA standard PS3 and as ISO standard 12052:2017: *"Health informatics – Digital imaging and communication in medicine (DICOM) including workflow and data management"*.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM is used worldwide to store, exchange, and transmit medical images.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM has been central to the development of modern radiological imaging; DICOM incorporates standards for imaging modalities such as radiography, ultrasonography, computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and radiation therapy.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM includes protocols for image exchange (e.g., via portable media such as DVDs), image compression, 3-D visualization, image presentation, and results reporting.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM is a standard developed by the American College of Radiology (ACR) and the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] In the beginning of the 1980s, it was difficult for anyone other than manufacturers of computed tomography or magnetic resonance imaging devices to decode the images that the machines generated.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Radiologists and medical physicists sought the images for dose-planning in radiation therapy.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] ACR and NEMA collaborated and formed a standard committee in 1983.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Their first standard, ACR/NEMA 300, entitled "Digital Imaging and Communications", was released in 1985.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Very soon after its release, it became clear that improvements were needed.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The text was vague and had internal contradictions.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] In 1988 the second version was released.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This version gained more acceptance among vendors.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The image transmission was specified as over a dedicated 2 pair cable (EIA-485).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The first demonstration of ACR/NEMA V2.0 interconnectivity technology was held at Georgetown University, May 21–23, 1990.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Six companies participated in this event, DeJarnette Research Systems, General Electric Medical Systems, Merge Technologies, Siemens Medical Systems, Vortech (acquired by Kodak that same year) and 3M.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Commercial equipment supporting ACR/NEMA 2.0 was presented at the annual meeting of the Radiological Society of North America (RSNA) in 1990 by these same vendors.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Many soon realized that the second version also needed improvement.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Several extensions to ACR/NEMA 2.0 were created, like Papyrus (developed by the University Hospital of Geneva, Switzerland) and SPI (Standard Product Interconnect), driven by Siemens Medical Systems and Philips Medical Systems.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The first large-scale deployment of ACR/NEMA technology was made in 1992 by the US Army and Air Force, as part of the MDIS (Medical Diagnostic Imaging Support) program based at Ft.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Loral Aerospace and Siemens Medical Systems led a consortium of companies in deploying the first US military PACS (Picture Archiving and Communications System) at all major Army and Air Force medical treatment facilities and teleradiology nodes at a large number of US military clinics.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DeJarnette Research Systems and Merge Technologies provided the modality gateway interfaces from third party imaging modalities to the Siemens SPI network.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The Veterans Administration and the Navy also purchased systems from this contract.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] In 1993 the third version of the standard was released.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Its name was then changed to "Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine", abbreviated DICOM.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] New service classes were defined, network support added and the Conformance Statement was introduced.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Initially the DICOM standard was referred to as "DICOM 3.0" to distinguish it from its predecessors.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM has been constantly updated and extended since 1993, with the intent that changes are backward compatible, except in rare cases where the earlier specification was incorrect or ambiguous.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Officially there is no "version" of the standard except the current standard, hence the "3.0" version number is no longer used.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] There are no "minor" versions to the standard (e.g., no such thing as "DICOM 3.1") and there are no current plans to develop a new, incompatible, version of the standard (i.e., no "DICOM 4.0").
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The standard should be referenced without specification of the date of release of a particular published edition, except when specific conformance requirements are invoked that depend on a retired feature that is no longer documented in the current standard.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] While the DICOM standard has achieved a near universal level of acceptance among medical imaging equipment vendors and healthcare IT organizations, the standard has its limitations.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM is a standard directed at addressing technical interoperability issues in medical imaging.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] It is not a framework or architecture for achieving a useful clinical workflow.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The Integrating the Healthcare Enterprise (IHE) initiative layered on top of DICOM (and HL-7) defines profiles to select features from these standards to implement transactions for specific medical imaging interoperability use cases.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Though always Internet compatible and based on transport over TCP, over time there has been an increasing need to support port 80 HTTP transport to make use easier within the web browser.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Most recently, a family of DICOM RESTful web services have been defined to allow mobile device friendly access to DICOM objects and services, which include WADO-RS, STOW-RS and QIDO-RS, which together constitute the DICOMweb initiative.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] There are some derivations from the DICOM standard into other application areas.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] These include DICONDE (*Digital Imaging and Communication in Nondestructive Evaluation*) that was established by ASTM International and DICOS (*Digital Imaging and Communication in Security*).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICONDE was established in 2004 as a way for nondestructive testing manufacturers and users to share image data.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICONDE can be used for computed radiography, digital radiography, computed tomography, ultrasonic testing, eddy-current testing, and thermographic testing.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICONDE is used worldwide to store, send, and exchange data from nondestructive material testing.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Unlike DICOM in the medical field, the adoption of DICONDE has been slower due to the lack of regulatory requirements for manufacturer-independent interoperability.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICONDE is also gaining importance in the context of Industry 4.0 due to its extensive capabilities for networking systems from different manufacturers.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOS was established in 2009 to be used for image sharing in airport security, cargo scanning, and other security applications.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The standard is published by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA) as NEMA IIC 1, and was developed in cooperation with the U.S.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Department of Homeland Security's Science and Technology Directorate and the Transportation Security Administration (TSA).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM groups information into data sets.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] For example, a file of a chest x-ray image may contain the patient ID within the file, so that the image can never be separated from this information by mistake.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This is similar to the way that image formats such as JPEG can also have embedded tags to identify and otherwise describe the image.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] A DICOM data object consists of a number of attributes, including items such as name, ID, etc., and also one special attribute containing the image pixel data (i.e. logically, the main object has no "header" as such, being merely a list of attributes, including the pixel data).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] A single DICOM object can have only one attribute containing pixel data.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] For many modalities, this corresponds to a single image.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] However, the attribute may contain multiple "frames", allowing storage of cine loops or other multi-frame data.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Another example is NM data, where an NM image, by definition, is a multi-dimensional multi-frame image.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] In these cases, three- or four-dimensional data can be encapsulated in a single DICOM object.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Pixel data can be compressed using a variety of standards, including JPEG, lossless JPEG, JPEG 2000, and run-length encoding (RLE).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] LZW (zip) compression can be used for the whole data set (not just the pixel data), but this has rarely been implemented.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM uses three different data element encoding schemes.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] With explicit value representation (VR) data elements, for VRs that are not OB, OW, OF, SQ, UT, or UN, the format for each data element is: GROUP (2 bytes) ELEMENT (2 bytes) VR (2 bytes) LengthInByte (2 bytes) Data (variable length).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] For the other explicit data elements or implicit data elements, see section 7.1 of Part 5 of the DICOM Standard.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The same basic format is used for all applications, including network and file usage, but when written to a file, usually a true "header" (containing copies of a few key attributes and details of the application that wrote it) is added.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] To promote identical grayscale image display on different monitors and consistent hard-copy images from various printers, the DICOM committee developed a lookup table to display digitally assigned pixel values.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] To use the **DICOM grayscale standard display function (GSDF)**, images must be viewed (or printed) on devices that have this lookup curve or on devices that have been calibrated to the GSDF curve.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] In addition to a value representation, each attribute also has a *value multiplicity* to indicate the number of data elements contained in the attribute.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] For character string value representations, if more than one data element is being encoded, the successive data elements are separated by the backslash character "\".
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM consists of services, most of which involve transmission of data over a network.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The file format for offline media is a later addition to the standard.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOM Store service is used to send images or other persistent objects (structured reports, etc.) to a picture archiving and communication system (PACS) or workstation.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOM storage commitment service is used to confirm that an image has been permanently stored by a device (either on redundant disks or on backup media, e.g. burnt to a CD).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The Service Class User (SCU: similar to a client), a modality or workstation, etc., uses the confirmation from the Service Class Provider (SCP: similar to a server), an archive station for instance, to make sure that it is safe to delete the images locally.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This enables a workstation to find lists of images or other such objects and then retrieve them from a picture archiving and communication system.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOM modality worklist service provides a list of imaging procedures that have been scheduled for performance by an image acquisition device (sometimes referred to as a modality system).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The items in the worklist include relevant details about the subject of the procedure (patient ID, name, sex, and age), the type of procedure (equipment type, procedure description, procedure code) and the procedure order (referring physician, accession number, reason for exam).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] An image acquisition device, such as a CT scanner, queries a service provider, such as a RIS, to get this information which is then presented to the system operator and is used by the imaging device to populate details in the image metadata.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Prior to the use of the DICOM modality worklist service, the scanner operator was required to manually enter all the relevant details.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Manual entry is slower and introduces the risk of misspelled patient names, and other data entry errors.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] A complementary service to modality worklist, this enables the modality to send a report about a performed examination including data about the images acquired, beginning time, end time, and duration of a study, dose delivered, etc.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] It helps give the radiology department a more precise handle on resource (acquisition station) use.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Also known as MPPS, this service allows a modality to better coordinate with image storage servers by giving the server a list of objects to send before or while actually sending such objects.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOM print service is used to send images to a DICOM printer, normally to print an "X-Ray" film.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] There is a standard calibration (defined in DICOM Part 14) to help ensure consistency between various display devices, including hard copy printout.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The format for offline media files is specified in Part 10 of the DICOM Standard.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Such files are sometimes referred to as "Part 10 files".
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM restricts the filenames on DICOM media to 8 characters (some systems wrongly use 8.3, but this does not conform to the standard).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] No information must be extracted from these names (PS3.10 Section 6.2.3.2).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This is a common source of problems with media created by developers who did not read the specifications carefully.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This is a historical requirement to maintain compatibility with older existing systems.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] It also mandates the presence of a media directory, the DICOMDIR file, which provides index and summary information for all the DICOM files on the media.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOMDIR information provides substantially greater information about each file than any filename could, so there is less need for meaningful file names.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM files typically have a .dcm file extension if they are not part of a DICOM media (which requires them to be without extension).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The MIME type for DICOM files is defined by RFC 3240 as `application/dicom`.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The Uniform Type Identifier type for DICOM files is `org.nema.dicom`.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] There is also an ongoing media exchange test and "connectathon" process for CD media and network operation that is organized by the IHE organization.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The core application of the DICOM standard is to capture, store and distribute medical images.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] DICOM has reserved the following TCP and UDP port numbers by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA): 104 well-known port for DICOM over Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The standard recommends but does not require the use of these port numbers.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] According to a paper presented at an international symposium in 2008, the DICOM standard has problems related to data entry.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] "A major disadvantage of the DICOM Standard is the possibility for entering probably too many optional fields.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This disadvantage is mostly showing in inconsistency of filling all the fields with the data.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Another disadvantage is that the file format admits executable code and may contain malware.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The DICOM standard is used in a wide variety of resources (IHE, HL7 ... a) that are related to images.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] The ISO12052: 2017 and CEN 12052 standards refer to the DICOM standard.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] In December 2023, cybersecurity researcher Sina Yazdanmehr unveiled a critical security issue within the Store service.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This revelation, presented at Black Hat Briefings, demonstrated the potential for malicious actors to manipulate existing series of medical images.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Yazdanmehr's research highlighted the alarming capability of attackers to destroy a series of images or introduce misleading indicators of illness.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Ensuring the security of patient data within DICOM is critical, as these files often contain sensitive personal health information (PHI).
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Security measures for DICOM data include encryption, access control, and auditing mechanisms to prevent unauthorized access, modification, or disclosure of patient information.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Compliance with regulations such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) in the United States and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) in Europe is essential for protecting patient privacy and ensuring the integrity of medical records.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] De-identification of DICOM refers to the process of removing or anonymizing personal health information (PHI) from medical images to protect patient privacy.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] This process is vital for sharing medical data for research, educational purposes, or public health activities while complying with privacy regulations.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Techniques for de-identification involve stripping out or masking identifiable data elements within the DICOM metadata, such as patient names, birth dates, and other unique identifiers.
[src:dicom-imaging/dicom] Ensuring thorough de-identification is crucial to balance the benefits of data sharing with the obligation to maintain patient confidentiality.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In a limited comparison, these technologies can be considered forms of medical imaging in another discipline of medical instrumentation.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As of 2010, 5 billion medical imaging studies had been conducted worldwide.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Radiation exposure from medical imaging in 2006 made up about 50% of total ionizing radiation exposure in the United States.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As of 2015, annual shipments of medical imaging chips amount to 46 million units and $1.1 billion.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The term "noninvasive" is used to denote a procedure where no instrument is introduced into a patient's body, which is the case for most imaging techniques used.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In 1972, engineer Godfrey Hounsfield from the British company EMI invented the X-ray computed tomography device for head diagnosis, which is commonly referred to as computed tomography (CT).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The CT nucleus method is based on the projecting X-rays through a section of the human head, which are then processed by computer to reconstruct the cross-sectional image, known as image reconstruction.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In 1975, EMI successfully developed a CT device for the entire body, enabling the clear acquisition of tomographic images of various parts of the human body.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This revolutionary diagnostic technique earned Hounsfield and physicist Allan Cormack the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1979.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Digital image processing technology for medical applications was inducted into the Space Foundation's Space Technology Hall of Fame in 1994.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] By 2010, over 5 billion medical imaging studies had been conducted worldwide.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Radiation exposure from medical imaging in 2006 accounted for about 50% of total ionizing radiation exposure in the United States.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As of 2015, annual shipments of medical imaging chips reached 46 million units, generating a market value of $1.1 billion.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In the clinical context, "invisible light" medical imaging is generally equated to radiology or "clinical imaging".
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] "Visible light" medical imaging involves digital video or still pictures that can be seen without special equipment.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Dermatology and wound care are two modalities that use visible light imagery.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Interpretation of medical images is generally undertaken by a physician specialising in radiology known as a *radiologist*; however, this may be undertaken by any healthcare professional who is trained and certified in radiological clinical evaluation.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Increasingly interpretation is being undertaken by non-physicians, for example radiographers frequently train in interpretation as part of expanded practice.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Diagnostic radiography designates the technical aspects of medical imaging and in particular the acquisition of medical images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The radiographer (also known as a radiologic technologist) is usually responsible for acquiring medical images of diagnostic quality; although other professionals may train in this area, notably some radiological interventions performed by radiologists are done so without a radiographer.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Many of the techniques developed for medical imaging also have scientific and industrial applications.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Two forms of radiographic images are in use in medical imaging.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Projection radiography and fluoroscopy, with the latter being useful for catheter guidance.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] These 2D techniques are still in wide use despite the advance of 3D tomography due to the low cost, high resolution, and depending on the application, lower radiation dosages with 2D technique.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This imaging modality uses a wide beam of X-rays for image acquisition and is the first imaging technique available in modern medicine.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The MRI machine emits a radio frequency (RF) pulse at the resonant frequency of the hydrogen atoms on water molecules.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Radio frequency antennas ("RF coils") send the pulse to the area of the body to be examined.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The RF pulse is absorbed by protons, causing their direction with respect to the primary magnetic field to change.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] When the RF pulse is turned off, the protons "relax" back to alignment with the primary magnet and emit radio waves in the process.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This radio-frequency emission from the hydrogen atoms on water is what is detected and reconstructed into an image.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The resonant frequency of a spinning magnetic dipole (of which protons are one example) is called the Larmor frequency and is determined by the strength of the main magnetic field and the chemical environment of the nuclei of interest.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Like CT, MRI traditionally creates a two-dimensional image of a thin "slice" of the body and is therefore considered a tomographic imaging technique.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Modern MRI instruments are capable of producing images in the form of 3D blocks, which may be considered a generalization of the single-slice, tomographic concept.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Unlike CT, MRI does not involve the use of ionizing radiation and is therefore not associated with the same health hazards.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] However, there are well-identified health risks associated with tissue heating from exposure to the RF field and the presence of implanted devices in the body, such as pacemakers.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] These risks are strictly controlled as part of the design of the instrument and the scanning protocols used.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Because CT and MRI are sensitive to different tissue properties, the appearances of the images obtained with the two techniques differ markedly.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In CT, X-rays must be blocked by some form of dense tissue to create an image, so the image quality when looking at soft tissues will be poor.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In MRI, while any nucleus with a net nuclear spin can be used, the proton of the hydrogen atom remains the most widely used, especially in the clinical setting, because it is so ubiquitous and returns a large signal.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This nucleus, present in water molecules, allows the excellent soft-tissue contrast achievable with MRI.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] A number of different pulse sequences can be used for specific MRI diagnostic imaging (multiparametric MRI or mpMRI).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] For example, imaging of prostate tumors is better accomplished using T2-MRI and DWI-MRI than T2-weighted imaging alone.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The number of applications of mpMRI for detecting disease in various organs continues to expand, including liver studies, breast tumors, pancreatic tumors, and assessing the effects of vascular disruption agents on cancer tumors.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Nuclear medicine encompasses both diagnostic imaging and treatment of disease, and may also be referred to as molecular medicine or molecular imaging and therapeutics.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Nuclear medicine uses certain properties of isotopes and the energetic particles emitted from radioactive material to diagnose or treat various pathology.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Different from the typical concept of anatomic radiology, nuclear medicine enables assessment of physiology.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This function-based approach to medical evaluation has useful applications in most subspecialties, notably oncology, neurology, and cardiology.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] *Gamma cameras* and *PET scanners* are used in e.g. scintigraphy, SPECT and PET to detect regions of biologic activity that may be associated with a disease.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Relatively short-lived isotope, such as 99mTc is administered to the patient.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Isotopes are often preferentially absorbed by biologically active tissue in the body, and can be used to identify tumors or fracture points in bone.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Images are acquired after collimated photons are detected by a crystal that gives off a light signal, which is in turn amplified and converted into count data.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Fiduciary markers are used in a wide range of medical imaging applications.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Images of the same subject produced with two different imaging systems may be correlated (called image registration) by placing a fiduciary marker in the area imaged by both systems.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In this case, a marker which is visible in the images produced by both imaging modalities must be used.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] By this method, functional information from SPECT or positron emission tomography can be related to anatomical information provided by magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Similarly, fiducial points established during MRI can be correlated with brain images generated by magnetoencephalography to localize the source of brain activity.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical ultrasound uses high frequency broadband sound waves in the megahertz range that are reflected by tissue to varying degrees to produce (up to 3D) images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This is commonly associated with imaging the fetus in pregnant women.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Uses of ultrasound are much broader, however.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Other important uses include imaging the abdominal organs, heart, breast, muscles, tendons, arteries and veins.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Ultrasound is also used as a popular research tool for capturing raw data, that can be made available through an ultrasound research interface, for the purpose of tissue characterization and implementation of new image processing techniques.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The concepts of ultrasound differ from other medical imaging modalities in the fact that it is operated by the transmission and receipt of sound waves.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The high frequency sound waves are sent into the tissue and depending on the composition of the different tissues; the signal will be attenuated and returned at separate intervals.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] A path of reflected sound waves in a multilayered structure can be defined by an input acoustic impedance (ultrasound sound wave) and the Reflection and transmission coefficients of the relative structures.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] It is very safe to use and does not appear to cause any adverse effects.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] It is also relatively inexpensive and quick to perform.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Ultrasound scanners can be taken to critically ill patients in intensive care units, avoiding the danger caused while moving the patient to the radiology department.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The real-time moving image obtained can be used to guide drainage and biopsy procedures.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Doppler capabilities on modern scanners allow the blood flow in arteries and veins to be assessed.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Elastography is a relatively new imaging modality that maps the elastic properties of soft tissue.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This modality emerged in the last two decades.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Elastography is useful in medical diagnoses, as elasticity can discern healthy from unhealthy tissue for specific organs/growths.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] For example, cancerous tumours will often be harder than the surrounding tissue, and diseased livers are stiffer than healthy ones.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] There are several elastographic techniques based on the use of ultrasound, magnetic resonance imaging and tactile imaging.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The wide clinical use of ultrasound elastography is a result of the implementation of technology in clinical ultrasound machines.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Main branches of ultrasound elastography include Quasistatic Elastography/Strain Imaging, Shear Wave Elasticity Imaging (SWEI), Acoustic Radiation Force Impulse imaging (ARFI), Supersonic Shear Imaging (SSI), and Transient Elastography.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In the last decade, a steady increase of activities in the field of elastography is observed demonstrating successful application of the technology in various areas of medical diagnostics and treatment monitoring.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Photoacoustic imaging is a recently developed hybrid biomedical imaging modality based on the photoacoustic effect.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] It combines the advantages of optical absorption contrast with an ultrasonic spatial resolution for deep imaging in (optical) diffusive or quasi-diffusive regime.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Recent studies have shown that photoacoustic imaging can be used in vivo for tumor angiogenesis monitoring, blood oxygenation mapping, functional brain imaging, and skin melanoma detection, etc.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Tomography is the imaging by sections or sectioning.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] When ultrasound is used to image the heart it is referred to as an echocardiogram.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Echocardiography allows detailed structures of the heart, including chamber size, heart function, the valves of the heart, as well as the pericardium (the sac around the heart) to be seen.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Echocardiography uses 2D, 3D, and Doppler imaging to create pictures of the heart and visualize the blood flowing through each of the four heart valves.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Echocardiography is widely used in an array of patients ranging from those experiencing symptoms, such as shortness of breath or chest pain, to those undergoing cancer treatments.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Transthoracic ultrasound has been proven to be safe for patients of all ages, from infants to the elderly, without risk of harmful side effects or radiation, differentiating it from other imaging modalities.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Echocardiography is one of the most commonly used imaging modalities in the world due to its portability and use in a variety of applications.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In emergency situations, echocardiography is quick, easily accessible, and able to be performed at the bedside, making it the modality of choice for many physicians.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] FNIR Is a relatively new non-invasive imaging technique.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] NIRS (near infrared spectroscopy) is used for the purpose of functional neuroimaging and has been widely accepted as a brain imaging technique.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Using superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles, magnetic particle imaging (MPI) is a developing diagnostic imaging technique used for tracking superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The primary advantage is the high sensitivity and specificity, along with the lack of signal decrease with tissue depth.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] MPI has been used in medical research to image cardiovascular performance, neuroperfusion, and cell tracking.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Organizations in the medical imaging industry include manufacturers of imaging equipment, freestanding radiology facilities, and hospitals.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The global market for manufactured devices was estimated at $5 billion in 2018.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Notable manufacturers included Fujifilm, GE HealthCare, Siemens Healthineers, Philips, Shimadzu, Canon, Carestream Health, Hologic, United Imaging, and Esaote.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In 2016, the manufacturing industry was characterized as oligopolistic and mature; new entrants included in Samsung and Neusoft Medical.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In 2024, Fischer MVL in India began manufacturing MRI machines.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Other companies in India include Allengers, Skanray, and BPL Medical Technologies.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In 2016, Toshiba exited the industry by selling its medical imaging division to Canon, which was ultimately renamed to Canon.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In 2019, Hitachi exited the industry by selling its business to Fujifilm for about $1.6 billion.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The simpler x-ray machines were being commoditized by 1998, when Kodak had about 30% market share globally; Kodak later sold its medical imaging business in 2007 and the business was ultimately renamed to Carestream Health.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In the 1970s, CT scanners were introduced, followed by MRI machines in the 1980s, with GE leading in both.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Digital radiography has replaced older computed radiography over time, which reduces radiation doses.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In the United States, as estimate as of 2015 places the US market for imaging scans at about $100b, with 60% occurring in hospitals and 40% occurring in freestanding clinics, such as the RadNet chain.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical imaging may be indicated in pregnancy because of pregnancy complications, a pre-existing disease or an acquired disease in pregnancy, or routine prenatal care.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) without MRI contrast agents as well as obstetric ultrasonography are not associated with any risk for the mother or the fetus, and are the imaging techniques of choice for pregnant women.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Projectional radiography, CT scan and nuclear medicine imaging result some degree of ionizing radiation exposure, but have with a few exceptions much lower absorbed doses than what are associated with fetal harm.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] At higher dosages, effects can include miscarriage, birth defects and intellectual disability.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The amount of data obtained in a single MR or CT scan is very extensive.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Some of the data that radiologists discard could save patients time and money, while reducing their exposure to radiation and risk of complications from invasive procedures.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Another approach for making the procedures more efficient is based on utilizing additional constraints, e.g., in some medical imaging modalities one can improve the efficiency of the data acquisition by taking into account the fact the reconstructed density is positive.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Volume rendering techniques have been developed to enable CT, MRI and ultrasound scanning software to produce 3D images for the physician.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Traditionally CT and MRI scans produced 2D static output on film.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] To produce 3D images, many scans are made and then combined by computers to produce a 3D model, which can then be manipulated by the physician.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] 3D ultrasounds are produced using a somewhat similar technique.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In diagnosing disease of the viscera of the abdomen, ultrasound is particularly sensitive on imaging of biliary tract, urinary tract and female reproductive organs (ovary, fallopian tubes).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As for example, diagnosis of gallstone by dilatation of common bile duct and stone in the common bile duct.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] With the ability to visualize important structures in great detail, 3D visualization methods are a valuable resource for the diagnosis and surgical treatment of many pathologies.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] It was a key resource for the famous, but ultimately unsuccessful attempt by Singaporean surgeons to separate Iranian twins Ladan and Laleh Bijani in 2003.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The 3D equipment was used previously for similar operations with great success.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Some of these techniques are still at a research stage and not yet used in clinical routines.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Neuroimaging has also been used in experimental circumstances to allow people (especially disabled persons) to control outside devices, acting as a brain computer interface.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Many medical imaging software applications are used for non-diagnostic imaging, specifically because they do not have an FDA approval and not allowed to use in clinical research for patient diagnosis.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Note that many clinical research studies are not designed for patient diagnosis anyway.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Used primarily in ultrasound imaging, capturing the image produced by a medical imaging device is required for archiving and telemedicine applications.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In most scenarios, a frame grabber is used in order to capture the video signal from the medical device and relay it to a computer for further processing and operations.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The Digital Imaging and Communication in Medicine (DICOM) Standard is used globally to store, exchange, and transmit medical images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The DICOM Standard incorporates protocols for imaging techniques such as radiography, computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), ultrasound, and radiation therapy.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] There has been growing trend to migrate from on-premise PACS to a cloud-based PACS, which can provide generative AI and other tools to improve diagnostic accuracy with greater fidelity and analysis, yet unresolved issues of bias and interpretation remain, as of 2025.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical imaging has become a major tool in clinical trials since it enables rapid diagnosis with visualization and quantitative assessment.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] A typical clinical trial goes through multiple phases and can take up to eight years.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Clinical endpoints or outcomes are used to determine whether the therapy is safe and effective.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Once a patient reaches the endpoint, he or she is generally excluded from further experimental interaction.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Trials that rely solely on clinical endpoints are very costly as they have long durations and tend to need large numbers of patients.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In contrast to clinical endpoints, surrogate endpoints have been shown to cut down the time required to confirm whether a drug has clinical benefits.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Imaging biomarkers (a characteristic that is objectively measured by an imaging technique, which is used as an indicator of pharmacological response to a therapy) and surrogate endpoints have shown to facilitate the use of small group sizes, obtaining quick results with good statistical power.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Imaging is able to reveal subtle change that is indicative of the progression of therapy that may be missed out by more subjective, traditional approaches.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Statistical bias is reduced as the findings are evaluated without any direct patient contact.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Imaging techniques such as positron emission tomography (PET) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) are routinely used in oncology and neuroscience areas.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] For example, measurement of tumour shrinkage is a commonly used surrogate endpoint in solid tumour response evaluation.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This allows for faster and more objective assessment of the effects of anticancer drugs.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In Alzheimer's disease, MRI scans of the entire brain can accurately assess the rate of hippocampal atrophy, while PET scans can measure the brain's metabolic activity by measuring regional glucose metabolism, and beta-amyloid plaques using tracers such as Pittsburgh compound B (PiB).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Historically less use has been made of quantitative medical imaging in other areas of drug development although interest is growing.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] An imaging centre that is responsible for collecting the images, perform quality control and provide tools for data storage, distribution and analysis.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] It is important for images acquired at different time points are displayed in a standardised format to maintain the reliability of the evaluation.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Certain specialised imaging contract research organizations provide end to end medical imaging services, from protocol design and site management through to data quality assurance and image analysis.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Clinical sites that recruit patients to generate the images to send back to the imaging centre.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical imaging can lead to patient and healthcare provider harm through exposure to ionizing radiation, iodinated contrast, magnetic fields, and other hazards.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Lead is the main material used for radiographic shielding against scattered X-rays.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In magnetic resonance imaging, there is MRI RF shielding as well as magnetic shielding to prevent external disturbance of image quality.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical imaging are generally covered by laws of medical privacy.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] While there has not been any definitive legal decision in the matter, many studies have indicated that medical imaging contain biometric information that can uniquely identify a person, and as such qualify as PHI and/or special categories of personal data.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The UK General Medical Council's ethical guidelines indicate that the Council does not require consent prior to making recordings of X-ray images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] However, the same guidance indicates that the images and recordings need to be anonimized, and acknowledges that in deciding whether a recording is anonymised, one should bear in mind that apparently insignificant details may still be capable of identifying a patient.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As such, one should be particularly careful about the anonymity of a recordings of an X-ray image before using or publishing them without consent in journals and other learning materials, whether they are printed or in an electronic format.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] As per chapter 300 of the *Compendium of U.S.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] While the Copyright Compendium is an agency statutory interpretation and not legally binding, courts are likely to give deference to it if they find it reasonable.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Yet, there is no U.S. federal case law directly addressing the issue of the copyrightability of X-ray images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] In Germany, X-ray images as well as MRI, medical ultrasound, PET and scintigraphy images are protected by (copyright-like) related rights or neighbouring rights.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This protection does not require creativity (as would be necessary for *regular* copyright protection) and lasts only for 50 years after image creation, if not published within 50 years, or for 50 years after the first legitimate publication.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The letter of the law grants this right to the "Lichtbildner", i.e. the person who created the image.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The literature seems to uniformly consider the medical doctor, dentist or veterinary physician as the rights holder, which may result from the circumstance that in Germany many X-rays are performed in ambulatory settings.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Medical images created in the United Kingdom will normally be protected by copyright due to "the high level of skill, labour and judgement required to produce a good quality X-ray, particularly to show contrast between bones and various soft tissues".
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The Society of Radiographers believe this copyright is owned by employer (unless the radiographer is self-employed—though even then their contract might require them to transfer ownership to the hospital).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] This copyright owner can grant certain permissions to whoever they wish, without giving up their ownership of the copyright.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] So the hospital and its employees will be given permission to use such radiographic images for the various purposes that they require for medical care.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Physicians employed at the hospital will, in their contracts, be given the right to publish patient information in journal papers or books they write (providing they are made anonymous).
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] Patients may also be granted permission to "do what they like with" their own images.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The *Cyber Law in Sweden* states: "Pictures can be protected as photographic works or as photographic pictures.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The former requires a higher level of originality; the latter *protects all types of photographs, also the ones taken* by amateurs, or *within medicine* or science.
[src:dicom-imaging/medical-imaging] The protection requires some sort of photographic technique being used, which includes digital cameras as well as holograms created by laser technique.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A **picture archiving and communication system** (**PACS**) is a medical imaging technology which provides economical storage and convenient access to images from multiple modalities (source machine types).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Electronic images and reports are transmitted digitally via PACS; this eliminates the need to manually file, retrieve, or transport film jackets, the folders used to store and protect X-ray film.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The universal format for PACS image storage and transfer is DICOM (Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Non-image data, such as scanned documents, may be incorporated using consumer industry standard formats like PDF (Portable Document Format), once encapsulated in DICOM.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Combined with available and emerging web technology, PACS has the ability to deliver timely and efficient access to images, interpretations, and related data.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] PACS reduces the physical and time barriers associated with traditional film-based image retrieval, distribution, and display.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Additional types of image formats are always being added.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Clinical areas beyond radiology; cardiology, oncology, gastroenterology, and even the laboratory are creating medical images that can be incorporated into PACS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] PACS is offered by virtually all the major medical imaging equipment manufacturers, medical IT companies and many independent software companies.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Basic PACS software can be found free on the Internet.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The architecture is the physical implementation of required functionality, or what one sees from the outside.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] There are different views, depending on the user.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A radiologist typically sees a viewing station, a technologist a QA workstation, while a PACS administrator might spend most of their time in the climate-controlled computer room.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The composite view is rather different for the various vendors.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Typically a PACS consists of a multitude of devices.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The first step in typical PACS systems is the modality.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Modalities are typically computed tomography (CT), ultrasound, nuclear medicine, positron emission tomography (PET), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Depending on the facility's workflow most modalities send to a quality assurance (QA) workstation, sometimes called a PACS gateway.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The QA workstation is a checkpoint to make sure patient demographics are correct as well as other important attributes of a study.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] If the study information is correct the images are passed to the archive for storage.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The central storage device (archive) stores images and in some cases reports, measurements and other information that resides with the images.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The next step in the PACS workflow is the reading workstations.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The reading workstation is where the radiologist reviews the patient's study and formulates their diagnosis.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Normally tied to the reading workstation is a reporting package that assists the radiologist with dictating the final report.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Reporting software is optional and there are various ways in which doctors prefer to dictate their report.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Ancillary to the workflow mentioned, there is normally CD/DVD authoring software used to burn patient studies for distribution to patients or referring physicians.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The diagram above shows a typical workflow in most imaging centers and hospitals.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Note that this section does not cover integration to a Radiology Information System, Hospital Information System and other such front-end system that relates to the PACS workflow.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] More and more PACS include web-based interfaces to utilize the internet or a wide area network (WAN) as their means of communication, usually via VPN (Virtual Private Network) or SSL (Secure Sockets Layer).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The clients side software may use ActiveX, JavaScript and/or a Java Applet.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] More robust PACS clients are full applications which can utilize the full resources of the computer they are executing on and are unaffected by the frequent unattended Web Browser and Java updates.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] As the need for distribution of images and reports becomes more widespread there is a push for PACS systems to support DICOM part 18 of the DICOM standard.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Web Access to DICOM Objects (WADO) creates the necessary standard to expose images and reports over the web through truly portable medium.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Without stepping outside the focus of the PACS architecture, WADO becomes the solution to cross platform capability and can increase the distribution of images and reports to referring physicians and patients.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] PACS image backup is a critical, but sometimes overlooked, part of the PACS Architecture (see below).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Within the United States, HIPAA requires that backup copies of patient images be made in case of image loss from the PACS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] There are several methods of backing up the images, but they typically involve automatically sending copies of the images to a separate computer for storage, preferably off-site.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The communication with the PACS server is done through DICOM messages that are similar to DICOM image "headers", but with different attributes.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Images (and other composite instances like Presentation States and Structured Reports) are then retrieved from a PACS server through either a C-MOVE or C-GET request, using the DICOM network protocol.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Retrieval can be performed at the Study, Series or Image (instance) level.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The C-MOVE request specifies where the retrieved instances should be sent (using separate C-STORE messages on one or more separate connections) with an identifier known as the destination Application Entity Title (AE Title).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] For a C-MOVE to work, the server must be configured with mapping of the AE Title to a TCP/IP address and port, and as a consequence the server must know in advance all the AE Titles that it will ever be requested to send images to.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A C-GET, on the other hand, performs the C-STORE operations on the same connection as the request, and hence does not require that the "server" know the "client" TCP/IP address and port.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] This allows C-GET to work more easily through firewalls and with network address translation, environments in which the incoming TCP C-STORE connections required for C-MOVE may not get through.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The difference between C-MOVE and C-GET is somewhat analogous to the difference between active and passive FTP.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] C-MOVE is most commonly used within enterprises and facilities, whereas C-GET is more practical between enterprises.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In addition to the traditional DICOM network services, particularly for cross-enterprise use, DICOM (and IHE) define other retrieval mechanisms, including WADO, WADO-WS and most recently WADO-RS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Digital medical images are typically stored locally on a PACS for retrieval.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] It is important (and required in the United States by the Security Rule's Administrative Safeguards section of HIPAA) that facilities have a means of recovering images in the event of an error or disaster.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] While each facility is different, the goal in image back-up is to make it automatic and as easy to administer as possible.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The hope is that the copies won't be needed; however, disaster recovery and business continuity planning dictates that plans should include maintaining copies of data even when an entire site is temporarily or permanently lost.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Ideally, copies of images should be maintained in several locations, including off-site to provide disaster recovery capabilities.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In general, PACS data are no different than other business critical data and should be protected with multiple copies at multiple locations.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] As PACS data can be considered protected health information (PHI), regulations may apply, most notably HIPAA and HIPAA Hi-Tech requirements.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Images may be stored both locally and remotely on off-line media such as disk, tape or optical media.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The use of storage systems, using modern data protection technologies has become increasingly common, particularly for larger organizations with greater capacity and performance requirements.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Storage systems may be configured and attached to the PACS server in various ways, either as Direct-Attached Storage (DAS), Network-attached storage (NAS), or via a Storage Area Network (SAN).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] However the storage is attached, enterprise storage systems commonly utilize RAID and other technologies to provide high availability and fault tolerance to protect against failures.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In the event that it is necessary to reconstruct a PACS partially or completely, some means of rapidly transferring data back to the PACS is required, preferably while the PACS continues to operate.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Modern data storage replication technologies may be applied to PACS information, including the creation of local copies via point-in-time copy for locally protected copies, along with complete copies of data on separate repositories including disk and tape based systems.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Remote copies of data should be created, either by physically moving tapes off-site, or copying data to remote storage systems.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Whenever HIPAA protected data are moved, it should be encrypted, which includes sending via physical tape or replication technologies over WAN to a secondary location.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Other options for creating copies of PACS data include removable media (hard drives, DVDs or other media that can hold many patients' images) that is physically transferred off-site.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] HIPAA HITECH mandates encryption of stored data in many instances or other security mechanisms to avoid penalties for failure to comply.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The back-up infrastructure may also be capable of supporting the migration of images to a new PACS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Due to the high volume of images that need to be archived many rad centers are migrating their systems to a Cloud-based PACS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A full PACS should provide a single point of access for images and their associated data.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] That is, it should support all digital modalities, in all departments, throughout the organisation.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] However, until PACS penetration is complete, individual islands of digital imaging not yet connected to a central PACS may exist.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] These may take the form of a localized, modality-specific network of modalities, workstations and storage (a so-called "mini-PACS"), or may consist of a small cluster of modalities directly connected to reading workstations without long-term storage or management.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Such systems are also often not connected to the departmental information system.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Historically, Ultrasound, Nuclear Medicine and Cardiology Cath Labs are often departments that adopt such an approach.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] More recently, Full Field digital mammography (FFDM) has taken a similar approach, largely because of the large image size, highly specialized reading workflow and display requirements, and intervention by regulators.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The rapid deployment of FFDM in the US following the DMIST study has led to the integration of Digital Mammography and PACS becoming more commonplace.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] All PACS, whether they span the entire enterprise or are localized within a department, should also interface with existing hospital information systems: Hospital information system (HIS) and Radiology Information System (RIS).
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Recognition of the importance of integration has led a number of suppliers to develop fully integrated RIS/PACS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The PACS installation process is complicated requiring time, resources, planning, and testing.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Installation is not complete until the acceptance test is passed.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Acceptance testing of a new installation is a vital step to assure user compliance, functionality, and especially clinical safety.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Take for example the Therac-25, a radiation medical device involved in accidents in which patients were given massive overdoses of radiation, due to unverified software control.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The acceptance test determines whether the PACS is ready for clinical use and marks the warranty timeline while serving as a payment milestone.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The test process varies in time requirements depending on facility size but contract condition of 30-day time limit is not unusual.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] It requires detailed planning and development of testing criteria prior to writing the contract.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] It is a joint process requiring defined test protocols and benchmarks.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A study determined that the most frequently cited deficiencies were the most costly components.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Failures ranked from most-to-least common are: Workstation; HIS/RIS/ACS broker interfaces; RIS; Computer Monitors; Web-based image distribution system; Modality interfaces; Archive devices; Maintenance; Training; Network; DICOM; Teleradiology; Security; Film digitizer.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] One of the first basic PACS was created in 1972 by Dr Richard J.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The principles of PACS were first discussed at meetings of radiologists in 1982.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Various people are credited with the coinage of the term *PACS*.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Cardiovascular radiologist Dr Andre Duerinckx reported in 1983 that he had first used the term in 1981.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Dr Samuel Dwyer, though, credits Dr Judith M.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Dr Harold Glass, a medical physicist working in London in the early 1990s secured UK Government funding and managed the project over many years which transformed Hammersmith Hospital in London as the first filmless hospital in the United Kingdom.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Dr Glass died a few months after the project came live but is credited with being one of the pioneers of PACS.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The first large-scale PACS installation was in 1982 at the University of Kansas, Kansas City.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In the US PACS are classified as Medical Devices, and hence if for sale are regulated by the USFDA.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In general they are subject to Class 2 controls and hence require a 510(k), though individual PACS components may be subject to less stringent general controls.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Some specific applications, such as the use for primary mammography interpretation, are additionally regulated within the scope of the Mammography Quality Standards Act.
[src:dicom-imaging/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The Society for Imaging Informatics in Medicine (SIIM) is the worldwide professional and trade organization that provides an annual meeting and a peer-reviewed journal to promote research and education about PACS and related digital topics.
[src:dicom-imaging/radiological-information-system] A **radiological information system** (**RIS**) is the core system for the electronic management of medical imaging departments.
[src:dicom-imaging/radiological-information-system] The major functions of the RIS can include patient scheduling, resource management, examination performance tracking, reporting, results distribution, and procedure billing.
[src:dicom-imaging/radiological-information-system] RIS complements HIS (hospital information systems) and PACS (picture archiving and communication system), and is critical to efficient workflow to radiology practices.
